# Narrative,,,,,,
XLII_admiral_narrative_grumium,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_grumium_wing",,"""I remember a raid on Athebyne's supply depots, some cycles ago. We were running low on everything - fuel, munitions, pilots. Lieutenant Reyes - solid flyer, came up through the reserves - took a squadron of Grumiums on what should've been a suicide run. Six wings, loaded heavy, against fortified emplacements and interceptor screens.""

""Lumbered in like cargo haulers. Reyes lost half his wing before they even lined up the shot. But the ones that made it through? Dropped their payload right into the heart of the depot. Chain reactions lit up the night side of the planet. We got the resupply we needed to hold the line another month.""

""Reyes brought three back. Got a commendation posthumously - caught a missile on the egress. The Grumium's no hero's ride. Slow, ugly work. But if it kills, it serves. And sometimes, that's all you need.""

A brief pause as the transfer finalizes.

""Commander.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_grumium_alt,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_grumium_alt_wing",,"""I remember a raid on Athebyne's supply depots, some cycles ago. We were running low on everything - fuel, munitions, pilots. Lieutenant Reyes - solid flyer, came up through the reserves - took a squadron of Grumiums on what should've been a suicide run. Six wings, loaded heavy, against fortified emplacements and interceptor screens.""

""Lumbered in like cargo haulers. Reyes lost half his wing before they even lined up the shot. But the ones that made it through? Dropped their payload right into the heart of the depot. Chain reactions lit up the night side of the planet. We got the resupply we needed to hold the line another month.""

""Reyes brought three back. Got a commendation posthumously - caught a missile on the egress. The Grumium's no hero's ride. Slow, ugly work. But if it kills, it serves. And sometimes, that's all you need.""

A brief pause as the transfer finalizes.

""Commander.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_alruba,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_alruba_fortysecond",,"""Most people look at her now and see a relic - ill fit for modern combat. But I remember when she was all we had.

Third week of the siege at Athebyne orbital. My flagship had taken a reactor hit, and I transferred my flag to the Resolute - an Alruba. We had six of them left in the picket line, facing down twice our number.

The captain - Walker, good officer - kept us between the troop transports and their missile boats. Took hits that would've gutted a Thuban. The armour held. Barely. By the time relief arrived, we'd lost three Alrubas, but the transports made it through.

Walker didn't. Reactor breach on the final push.

The Alruba's not fast. Not elegant. But she's honest. And doesn't quit until she's a debris field. Sometimes that's enough.""

A brief pause as the data finalizes.

""That'll be all, Commander.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_shaobi,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_shaobi_fortysecond",,"""The Shaobi. The Marines' favourite toy. Command didn't want to build her - too specialised, too expensive. But the Marines made their case, and somehow, it stuck.

I'll admit, I didn't see the value. Not at first.

Then came the boarding operation at Ring-Port - back when it was still under separatist control. We needed to take the station intact, and orbital bombardment wasn't an option. That meant Marines. Lots of them.

The Shaobi-class Warhound led the assault. Two hundred Marines, full combat load, deployed in under twenty minutes. They hit three docking points simultaneously - precision insertion, no warning.

The captain - Major Hartley, Marine Corps - she coordinated the whole thing from the Warhound's bridge. Ship-to-boarding-craft comms, real-time tactical updates, fire support from the gunship's turrets. It wasn't just a carrier - it was a forward command post with engines.

We took Ring-Port in six hours. Minimal casualties. Hartley got a medal. The Warhound got a reputation.

The Shaobi's not a fleet carrier. She's not meant to be. But if you need boots on a station or a hostile ship, she'll get them there - and bring them home.

Sometimes that's worth more than another fighter wing.""

A pause.

""The Alliance chose well with you, Commander. Transfer authorized.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_errakis,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_errakis_fortysecond",,"""A carrier escort strictly speaking. Compromised sensors to save weight and meet project requirements. Command signed off on it because she was never meant to operate independently.

That became a problem during the push on Athebyne's outer stations. We had the Milwaukee - assigned to screen the Io's carrier group. Standard formation, textbook deployment. Then the carrier's sensor array took a hit from long-range fire. Partial failure - enough to briefly shunt the datalink, not enough to justify pulling back.

The Milwaukee was supposed to provide missile support. But with the carrier's sensors degraded and her own array already limited, she couldn't get a clean firing solution on anything beyond visual range. Captain Holt - had a ship full of ordnance and nothing to shoot at.

So he did what the ship wasn't designed to do: he moved in close. Uncomfortably close.

The Milwaukee took more hits in that engagement than any other ship in the group. Lost two crew compartments, vented half her missile reserves in an ammunition cook off. But the carrier stayed operational, and the screen held.""

Your sensors officer glances back at you, eyebrows raised. Authorization codes transmitted.

""Until next time, Commander.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_juza,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_juza_fortysecond",,"""Even while it serves it's considered a 'prototype'. Armoured like a battleship, just fast enough to keep up with cruiser squadrons. On paper, she's perfect. In practice? A damned miracle - when she works.

At end of the war had four Juzas in active service. The Jericho was flagship for the third battle group - my XO's command. Fleet engagement near Athebyne's inner belt. Standard line battle, cruiser-on-cruiser.

Then the Jericho's flux regulators spiked. Total system failure - her shields dropped, her weapons went cold. A paperweight in the middle of a firing line.

Her chief engineer - man named Nowak, stubborn bastard - he rerouted power through the secondary grid, bypassed the safeties, and brought the flux system back online in under three minutes. A miracle to put it bluntly.

By the time the Jericho came back, she'd taken fourteen direct hits. Her armour held. Barely. Nowak kept her running for another six hours before the system burned out for good. We won that engagement.

The Juza's temperamental. High-maintenance. But if you've got a crew that knows her quirks, she'll hold the line when everything else breaks.""

A brief silence followed by an authorization code transmission.

""Authorization granted.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_alwaid,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_alwaid_fortysecond",,"""I've heard the jokes - ""by the time she arrives, the war's over."" The crews call her the 'Late Arrival.'

An anecdote: Textbook carrier doctrine. Three battlegroups were to warp directly into the fight. The Alwaid's group? Delayed by a drive malfunction - forty minutes late to the fight.

By the time they arrived, we'd lost Heaven's Axiom and half her escort. The Diligence was burning, venting atmosphere from six hull breaches. We were fifteen minutes from a full retreat.

Then the Eternity translated in-system. Two hundred and sixty fighters. Every torpedo tube loaded. She didn't win the battle herself - but she ended it. The enemy scattered. We held the orbitals.

The Alwaid's slow. But when she gets there, she brings everything.""

The faintest pause.

""It's yours.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_tianlong,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,"$XLII_store_selected == XLII_tianlong_fortysecond",,"""Four cycles ago, a Pather raiding flotilla entered Kori's orbital space in coordination with a surface sabotage operation. The intent was to occupy our response force long enough for the ground teams to finish their work. The Covenant was in the patrol rotation.

Vasile, her commander, took her through the centre of the formation. Struck their lead ship at speed, engaged the second at close range, and repositioned between the flotilla and their egress vector before their command element had processed what had happened. The aft section took heavy damage. Prioritised forward coverage with the rear mount. But even so, the flotilla broke. The surface teams lost their extraction window.

The after-action report was four pages. Three and a half of them were just damage assessments. The remaining half-page described his tactical reasoning in language I found adequate but incomplete. He did not mention that the Covenant's approach vector was inconsistent with any evasive option - that closing at that speed, on that bearing, was not a response to the engagement. It was a conclusion he had reached before the engagement began.

He is a precise man. His logs are immaculate. I do not think the imprecision was accidental.""

A silence. Although not long.

""Take good care of her, Commander. The Alliance has few enough of these.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue",
XLII_admiral_narrative_generic,XLII_AdmiralNarrative,,,"""A capable hull."" He keys something on the console. ""Authorization complete.""

A brief pause as the transfer finalizes.

""Good hunting, Commander.""","1:transaction_complete:Continue","Fallback narrative for any store item without a specific story"
XLII_admiral_accept,DialogOptionSelected,"$option == transaction_complete",,"The figure inclines his head slightly. ""Officers like you are why we'll survive what's coming. Safe travels, Commander.""","1:reopen_store:Browse more vessels.
2:dismiss:End transmission",
XLII_admiral_decline,DialogOptionSelected,"$option == decline",,"""The offer stands. When you're ready, whenever that may be, the authorization remains active in your file."" A beat. ""However, we don't make these offers lightly, Commander""

The briefest hesitation.

His hand moves, beginning the process of closing the connection. ""You know how to reach us.""","1:reopen_store:Actually, let me take another look.
2:dismiss:End transmission",
XLII_admiral_dismiss,DialogOptionSelected,"$option == dismiss","EndConversation","The transmission ends.",,
"#END Narrative",,,,,,
"#END Fleet Admiral's Store Menu",,,,,,
"#END Fleet Admiral's Store",,,,,,
